def get_last_element_by_index(lst, index):
    return lst[index % len(lst)]

# Example usage:
print(get_last_element_by_index(my_list, 0))  # prints the last element of my_list
print(get_last_element_by_index(my_list, 1))  # prints the second-to-last element of my_list
print(get_last_element_by_index(my_list, 10))  # prints the 10th element of my_list (or the first element if index is out of range)
```

This code defines a function `get_last_element_by_index` that takes a list and an index as arguments. The function returns the last element in the list that corresponds to the given index, taking into account cases where the index exceeds the length of the list.

The example usage demonstrates how to use this function with different indices to retrieve elements from the `my_list`."

